### Finding 5: `last_sent_times_` State Shared Across Group Becomes Incorrect for Non-Representative Clients

**File**: `/home/davide/ws_plotjuggler/src/pj_ros_bridge/app/src/bridge_server.cpp`
**Lines**: 652-699

```cpp
const auto& representative_subs = client_subs[client_ids.front()];
auto& rep_last_sent = last_sent_times_[client_ids.front()];

// ... rate limiting loop updates rep_last_sent ...

// Propagate rate-limiting state to other clients in the group
for (const auto& client_id : client_ids) {
    if (client_id != client_ids.front()) {
        last_sent_times_[client_id] = rep_last_sent;  // full copy
    }
}
```

This copies the representative's *entire* `last_sent_times_` map to every other client in the group. If a non-representative client previously had `last_sent_times_` entries for topics it is no longer subscribed to (from a previous subscription configuration), those stale entries are obliterated by this assignment. More importantly, if a client moves between groups across publish cycles (because it changed its rate on one topic), its `last_sent_times_` for topics not in the current group are wiped out, potentially causing a burst of messages on its next group assignment when those topics are checked.

**Impact**: Stale rate-limiting state loss can cause brief message bursts or incorrect rate limiting after subscription changes.

**Severity**: Low-to-medium.

