### Bug #7 (Medium): clients_mutex_ held during send operations

**Analysis**

In `websocket_middleware.cpp`, `send_reply()` (line 217), `send_binary()` (line 229), and `publish_data()` (line 242) all hold `clients_mutex_` while calling IXWebSocket's `send()` or `sendBinary()`. These are network I/O operations that may block if the client has TCP backpressure. Holding the mutex during I/O blocks all other operations that need the clients map.

**Recommended approach**: Copy the `shared_ptr<ix::WebSocket>` under the lock, release the lock, then send.

**Implementation**

For `send_reply()`:
```cpp
bool WebSocketMiddleware::send_reply(const std::string& client_identity, const std::vector<uint8_t>& data) {
    std::shared_ptr<ix::WebSocket> ws;
    {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(clients_mutex_);
        auto it = clients_.find(client_identity);
        if (it == clients_.end() || !it->second) {
            return false;
        }
        ws = it->second;
    }
    // Send outside lock -- if client disconnects concurrently, ix::WebSocket handles it safely
    std::string text_data(data.begin(), data.end());
    auto send_info = ws->send(text_data);
    return send_info.success;
}
```

Apply the same pattern to `send_binary()`:
```cpp
bool WebSocketMiddleware::send_binary(const std::string& client_identity, const std::vector<uint8_t>& data) {
    std::shared_ptr<ix::WebSocket> ws;
    {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(clients_mutex_);
        auto it = clients_.find(client_identity);
        if (it == clients_.end() || !it->second) {
            return false;
        }
        ws = it->second;
    }
    std::string binary_data(reinterpret_cast<const char*>(data.data()), data.size());
    auto send_info = ws->sendBinary(binary_data);
    return send_info.success;
}
```

For `publish_data()`, copy all shared_ptrs into a local vector:
```cpp
bool WebSocketMiddleware::publish_data(const std::vector<uint8_t>& data) {
    std::vector<std::shared_ptr<ix::WebSocket>> clients_snapshot;
    {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(clients_mutex_);
        if (clients_.empty()) {
            return false;
        }
        clients_snapshot.reserve(clients_.size());
        for (const auto& [id, ws] : clients_) {
            if (ws) {
                clients_snapshot.push_back(ws);
            }
        }
    }
    std::string binary_data(reinterpret_cast<const char*>(data.data()), data.size());
    bool any_sent = false;
    for (const auto& ws : clients_snapshot) {
        auto send_info = ws->sendBinary(binary_data);
        if (send_info.success) {
            any_sent = true;
        }
    }
    return any_sent;
}
```

**Safety**: `ix::WebSocket` is a `shared_ptr`-managed object. The `send()`/`sendBinary()` methods are thread-safe (IXWebSocket uses internal write locking). If the client disconnects while we hold the `shared_ptr`, the WebSocket object remains alive until we release it, and the send will simply fail. The `clients_` map is only modified under `clients_mutex_`, and the Close callback (which erases from `clients_`) runs on the IX IO thread -- it will wait for our lock to be released, but since we already copied the pointer, the erase is safe.

**Files to modify**:
- `/home/davide/ws_plotjuggler/src/pj_ros_bridge/app/src/middleware/websocket_middleware.cpp` -- change `send_reply()`, `send_binary()`, `publish_data()`

**Edge cases**:
- Client disconnects between copying the `shared_ptr` and calling `send()`: IXWebSocket's `send()` returns `{success: false}`. Handled correctly.
- Client reconnects with the same ID during send: The old `shared_ptr` still points to the old WebSocket. The new connection gets a new entry in `clients_`. No conflict.
- Shutdown between copying and sending: The shared_ptr keeps the WebSocket alive. The send will fail but won't crash.

**Tests to write**:
1. The existing `SendReplyToConnectedClient`, `SendBinaryToConnectedClient`, and `ShutdownWithConnectedClientDoesNotDeadlock` tests cover the basic correctness. After the change, these should still pass.
2. `SendDoesNotBlockOtherSends` -- (Integration-level) Connect two clients. Send a large binary to client A while simultaneously sending to client B. Verify both complete without excessive delay. This is hard to unit-test purely but can be verified with TSAN.

